  "prompt": "What is the difference between Raw and Smackdown in WWE?",
  "response": "WWE Raw and WWE SmackDown are the two main weekly television programs produced by World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE). They differ in several ways:\n\n1. **Broadcast Days**:\n   - *WWE Raw*: Traditionally airs on Monday nights.\n   - *WWE SmackDown*: Traditionally airs on Friday nights.\n\n2. **Brand Distinction**:\n   - The distinction between Raw and SmackDown is part of WWE's \"brand split,\" which means the shows are treated as separate entities with distinct rosters of wrestlers. This allows for unique storylines and rivalries specific to each show.\n\n3. **Color Themes**:\n   - *WWE Raw*: Often associated with the color red.\n   - *WWE SmackDown*: Often associated with the color blue.\n\n4. **History and Origins**:\n   - *WWE Raw*: Premiered in January 1993 and is known for being WWE's flagship program. It has longer episodes, typically lasting three hours.\n   - *WWE SmackDown*: Premiered in April 1999 and was initially considered the \"secondary\" show. Episodes are typically two hours long.\n\n5. **Production Style and Emphasis**:\n   - *WWE Raw*: Sometimes emphasizes more dramatic storylines, backstage segments, and extended promos along with wrestling.\n   - *WWE SmackDown*: Generally focuses more on in-ring wrestling action, but this can vary depending on the current creative direction.\n\n6. **Championship Titles**:\n   - Throughout the brand split, there are distinct championships for each show. Raw and SmackDown have their own sets of title belts such as the WWE Championship (Raw) and the Universal Championship (SmackDown).\n\n7. **Wrestler Participation**:\n   - While typically wrestlers are exclusive to one show due to the brand split, there have been periods where wrestlers crossed over due to special events, inter-brand rivalries, or temporary suspension of the brand split.\n\nThese differences contribute to each brand\u2019s unique identity while still being part of the larger WWE universe.",
